463
00:36:15,755 --> 00:36:17,830
Rym: So what is a scanner in a nutshell?

464
00:36:18,311 --> 00:36:28,710
Rym: It's a device which, remember, these appeared and were used long before things like smartphones or even digital cameras existed, to give you the context.

465
00:36:28,830 --> 00:36:30,969
Rym: You really got to remember that context.

466
00:36:31,571 --> 00:36:46,550
Rym: In the old days, if you had a computer of any kind and you wanted to get an image into that computer, you had originally one option, and that one option was draw it pixels with pixels somehow.

467
00:36:48,052 --> 00:36:55,310
Rym: And then an invention appeared to capture photons and generate an image file from photons.

468
00:36:55,751 --> 00:37:00,030
Rym: That is the origin of both digital cameras and the origin of scanners, essentially.

469
00:37:01,270 --> 00:37:02,979
Scott: Yeah, well, I mean, we had the copy machine, right?

470
00:37:05,150 --> 00:37:15,270
Scott: So the original scanners, as far as I'm aware, at least for computers, weren't too different from the mechanism in copy machines of the time.

471
00:37:15,812 --> 00:37:21,389
Scott: The only difference was that instead of immediately just printing a copy straightaway...

472
00:37:21,830 --> 00:37:27,290
Rym: Well, well, that's already kind of, because a lot of copy machines were not really digital and were using...

473
00:37:27,870 --> 00:37:30,061
Scott: No, yeah, you're talking about the original Xeroxes?

474
00:37:30,101 --> 00:37:31,830
Scott: Yeah, those worked completely differently.

475
00:37:32,030 --> 00:37:42,750
Rym: Yeah, so once you got to the point where there was a memory buffer with the image that was being scanned that was used to put the output to the paper, that's the era you were talking about.

476
00:37:43,393 --> 00:37:44,619
Scott: Yeah, exactly, right?

477
00:37:45,061 --> 00:37:46,750
Scott: So, you know, you think about it, right?

478
00:37:46,810 --> 00:37:55,070
Scott: It's like you had these devices that were somewhat, in principle, like a laser printer with a scanner attached directly to it, right?

479
00:37:55,230 --> 00:37:58,149
Scott: It's like it's scanned and immediately laser print, you know.

480
00:37:58,672 --> 00:38:01,030
Scott: We've done a show on printers and how laser printers work, right?

481
00:38:01,151 --> 00:38:02,540
Scott: So you can listen to that.

482
00:38:02,601 --> 00:38:03,850
Scott: It's a hundred years old episode.

483
00:38:05,711 --> 00:38:08,138
Scott: So when we had computers, right?

484
00:38:08,158 --> 00:38:21,870
Scott: I think in the 90s, the scanners came into existence, at least as an expensive consumer product, the flatbed scanner, and you'd hook it up to your SCSI ports, your parallel ports, or your serial ports, or whatever, before USB existed.

485
00:38:22,731 --> 00:38:27,930
Scott: And you slap a piece of paper down on there, you close the lid, and it would scan it slowly.

486
00:38:29,171 --> 00:38:29,352
Scott: Yep.

487
00:38:29,873 --> 00:38:39,170
Rym: Actually, my first scanner, so I never had a scanner that we owned, that I had access to directly, just in our house, until late middle school.

488
00:38:41,212 --> 00:38:50,330
Rym: And we actually got a SCSI scanner that was about ten times faster than a serial port or like printer port scanner.

489
00:38:51,430 --> 00:38:51,490
Scott: Yep.

490
00:38:51,752 --> 00:38:56,989
