502
00:39:55,730 --> 00:39:58,409
Scott: It's like you could put that now on a website or share it.

503
00:39:58,530 --> 00:40:07,042
Scott: It's like now, taking a photo and sharing it is the most basic common functionality, but it's also the most fun thing.

504
00:40:07,082 --> 00:40:09,030
Scott: People still love the fuck out of doing that.

505
00:40:09,511 --> 00:40:14,229
Scott: It's like one of the number one uses of phones is take pictures and share them.

506
00:40:15,092 --> 00:40:17,409
Scott: So it's like that wasn't possible to do.

507
00:40:17,710 --> 00:40:21,363
Scott: And then if you had a scanner, you could kind of do it, and it was pretty exciting.

508
00:40:25,531 --> 00:40:33,988
Rym: So the basic kinds of scanners that existed and still exist were the flatbed ones that you can put a document or a picture or really anything in.

509
00:40:35,392 --> 00:40:36,637
Rym: It looks like a Xerox machine.

510
00:40:37,400 --> 00:40:41,315
Rym: There's the ones that are sort of sheet fed, so it looks like a printer.

511
00:40:41,355 --> 00:40:47,089
Rym: You put a piece of paper, usually a document in it, and it'll just pull it through and scan it.

512
00:40:47,590 --> 00:40:49,750
Scott: Yeah, that's not too different from the flatbed one.

513
00:40:49,810 --> 00:41:01,548
Scott: The difference is that in the flatbed one, the bar that's doing the scanning is moving and the paper is still, whereas in the sheet fed one, it's like, well, the bar is still and the paper moves across.

514
00:41:02,510 --> 00:41:06,483
Rym: There are pros and cons to both approaches, but that doesn't matter that much, and we'll get to that.

515
00:41:07,892 --> 00:41:15,890
Scott: If you're scanning negatives, you can scan film negatives the flatbed way, but they also have these drum scanners that are pretty popular.

516
00:41:16,978 --> 00:41:18,350
Rym: I would say that photo scanners.

517
00:41:18,912 --> 00:41:20,321
Scott: You're not going to have one of those at home.

518
00:41:20,421 --> 00:41:26,269
Scott: Photo labs are going to use those, and the reason they use those is because you can scan negatives very quickly with the drum scanner.

519
00:41:27,891 --> 00:41:32,170
Scott: It's like you get speed and quality, and the downside is big machine.

520
00:41:32,951 --> 00:41:39,309
