586
00:46:53,698 --> 00:47:03,169
Scott: if you are a household in the world today and you still for some reason need to scan and print, that's the kind of device that you're going to have.

587
00:47:03,630 --> 00:47:18,450
Rym: But where I was going, all those old consumer scanners from 20 plus years ago, they work just fine today, but almost categorically, the companies that sold that hardware just don't have drivers for any modern operating system.

588
00:47:18,872 --> 00:47:20,903
Scott: Well, because it's an old unsupported device.

589
00:47:20,963 --> 00:47:22,270
Scott: Why would they update their driver?

590
00:47:23,653 --> 00:47:28,430
Scott: You can often use the generic, there's like a standard called TWAIN.

591
00:47:28,610 --> 00:47:29,749
Rym: I was going to bring up TWAIN.

592
00:47:30,231 --> 00:47:32,246
Scott: I never knew what TWAIN stood for my whole life.

593
00:47:32,306 --> 00:47:32,830
Scott: I still don't.

594
00:47:32,970 --> 00:47:34,690
Scott: I guess I could Google it right now and find out.

595
00:47:34,730 --> 00:47:38,070
Rym: I look it up every time it comes up and then I forget it immediately after.

596
00:47:38,730 --> 00:47:42,950
Scott: TWAIN is basically some standard protocol for scanners to talk to computers.

597
00:47:43,532 --> 00:47:44,054
Rym: Oh, no.

598
00:47:44,114 --> 00:47:44,957
Rym: You know why?

599
00:47:45,058 --> 00:47:46,081
Rym: We never remember.

600
00:47:46,101 --> 00:47:48,530
Rym: It's not actually an acronym.

601
00:47:49,651 --> 00:47:50,574
Rym: It's a background.

602
00:47:50,896 --> 00:47:54,829
Rym: It was just called TWAIN and then people made up what it stood for.

603
00:47:55,650 --> 00:47:56,212
Scott: Oh, okay.

604
00:47:56,252 --> 00:48:06,350
Scott: But anyway, it's basically a protocol for scanners and computers to talk to each other in a standard way so that you could get a computer that knows how to speak TWAIN and a scanner that knows how to speak TWAIN.

605
00:48:06,811 --> 00:48:09,850
Scott: And then, look, you can scan even if you don't have a driver.

606
00:48:10,211 --> 00:48:20,950
Scott: The problem is that the drivers, the official drivers for a particular scanner, will often provide you with lots and lots of extra features that are often not part of the TWAIN standard.

607
00:48:21,230 --> 00:48:24,630
Rym: And depending on what kind of scanner it is, they're either helpful or annoying.

608
00:48:25,470 --> 00:48:25,953
Scott: Right.

609
00:48:26,033 --> 00:48:32,590
Scott: And then if you just use TWAIN, like a generic scanner driver, your options for scanning are going to be very, very limited.

610
00:48:32,930 --> 00:48:35,585
Scott: It's pretty much going to be scan a page, the end.

611
00:48:35,605 --> 00:48:36,249
Scott: That's all you can do.

612
00:48:36,912 --> 00:48:43,870
Rym: Well, as the software does, I actually have been using TWAIN quite a bit because I've been doing a lot of scanning over the last few years for a bunch of reasons.

613
00:48:44,612 --> 00:48:45,758
Rym: So I'm going to read first.

614
00:48:46,080 --> 00:48:51,410
Rym: Here is actually what TWAIN stands for, unless this is someone has vandalized Wikipedia just recently.

615
00:48:52,573 --> 00:48:54,429
Rym: "The word TWAIN is not an acronym but a backronym.

616
00:48:54,790 --> 00:49:06,968
Rym: The official website notes that the word TWAIN is from Kipling's 'The Ballad of East and West' and the line 'And never the TWAIN shall meet,' reflecting the difficulty at the time of connecting scanners to personal

617
00:49:07,008 --> 00:49:07,390
Rym: computers.".

618
00:49:08,733 --> 00:49:08,950
Scott: Uh-huh.

619
00:49:09,410 --> 00:49:14,810
Rym: That's the best explanation for the name of a computer thing that I've seen in a long time.

620
00:49:15,070 --> 00:49:16,130
Rym: That's actually kind of funny.

621
00:49:17,190 --> 00:49:17,373
Scott: All right.

622
00:49:17,394 --> 00:49:18,209
Scott: I learned something today.

623
00:49:18,511 --> 00:49:19,436
Rym: I learned something, too.

624
00:49:19,497 --> 00:49:21,368
Rym: This is why I keep forgetting this every time I look it up.

625
00:49:21,870 --> 00:49:29,470
Rym: But I have an ancient, ancient Canon scanner that there's no driver on Earth for a modern computer.

626
00:49:30,773 --> 00:49:34,890
Rym: It plugs into a USB 3, but it's definitely just USB 2.

627
00:49:34,890 --> 00:49:36,670
Rym: But the hardware is totally fine.

628
00:49:37,190 --> 00:49:47,070
Rym: So the way I use it is I'll either have Photoshop use TWAIN to control it directly, scan directly into Photoshop, or I'll have Adobe Acrobat use it directly.

629
00:49:47,692 --> 00:49:49,930
Scott: Adobe Acrobat directly scanning is pretty good, actually.

630
00:49:50,090 --> 00:49:51,390
Rym: Adobe Acrobat directly scanning.

631
00:49:51,610 --> 00:49:55,344
Rym: Like, talking about the side benefits of paying for Creative Cloud.

632
00:49:55,364 --> 00:49:58,990
Rym: if you need some Adobe software and you just get everything else along with the ride.

633
00:49:59,871 --> 00:50:08,150
Rym: If you've got, say, a bunch of old documents like, I don't know, car maintenance receipts or, uh, leases that you want to scan.

634
00:50:08,270 --> 00:50:15,249
Rym: Like, you want to throw away old papers, but you want to scan them in and save them as PDFs in case you need them to give to a lawyer 20 years from now.

635
00:50:16,190 --> 00:50:22,929
Rym: Adobe Acrobat is a really great way to do that because you just batch up these scannings and it'll just make a PDF for you one by one.

636
00:50:24,774 --> 00:50:34,728
Scott: Alright, so the thing I want to talk about that's, like, you know, I guess not super recent, but basically the current deal of scanning is that for high resolution, high quality scans.

637
00:50:34,788 --> 00:50:44,469
Scott: these days, a lot of people, like, in the photo world, but also other worlds, right, have basically abandoned scanners, right, as the way to go.

638
00:50:45,190 --> 00:50:48,190
Scott: Instead, people are just using digital cameras.

639
00:50:48,651 --> 00:51:17,550
Scott: It's like, if you just take whatever it is that you want to scan, say, a negative or a photo or magazine or whatever, you just line it up flat on some surface, right, light it appropriately with lights, right, to get evenly lit, get a digital camera with an appropriate lens, mount the camera aiming straight down, right, line everything up, you know, do the manual focus and take a picture.

640
00:51:18,330 --> 00:51:21,018
Scott: And that's going to be the digital cameras.

641
00:51:21,058 --> 00:51:34,350
Scott: now, even if you use your phone, are so good, right, that, like, first of all, this is going to, A, the quality, it might beat a lot of almost all scanners.

642
00:51:35,030 --> 00:51:42,829
Rym: Especially because a lot of apps or a lot of pipelines to do this with phones will do things like if you take the photo at an angle, it'll correct for that.

643
00:51:43,590 --> 00:51:47,490
Scott: Yeah, there's all kinds of software that helps this process, makes it easier, makes it better.

644
00:51:48,590 --> 00:52:01,590
Scott: But also, in terms of the speed of the process, it's like, if you want to scan something, it's like, all right, line it up, change these settings, push scan, wait, get a document.

645
00:52:02,871 --> 00:52:09,050
Scott: It's like, right, if you've just taken photos as scanning, right, it's like, click, there it is.

646
00:52:09,110 --> 00:52:14,230
Scott: It already goes directly from the physical world into the exact end place.

647
00:52:14,310 --> 00:52:19,790
Scott: You're bypassing all this, like, scanning process, all the manual labor of scanning things, right.

648
00:52:19,870 --> 00:52:21,699
Scott: It's just sort of eliminated, right.

649
00:52:22,571 --> 00:52:25,729
Scott: It's like, oh, I just now have an SD card that has all my files on it.

650
00:52:27,255 --> 00:52:28,509
Scott: It's like, you're good to go.

651
00:52:29,890 --> 00:52:44,930
Scott: You know, the only times that this process might be a little cumbersome is the final topic of scanning, which has been, I guess, what is OCR, right, which stands for optical character recognition.

652
00:52:45,090 --> 00:53:05,210
Scott: And this is sort of not necessarily scanning itself, but a post scanning process where, okay, you scanned something, you've turned a physical, you know, flat document into an image, a JPEG, a TIFF or whatever image file, but you didn't actually want to create a raster image of a thing like a photo.

653
00:53:05,731 --> 00:53:13,070
Scott: You wanted the words in some alphabet translated not into a JPEG, but into a text file.

654
00:53:13,090 --> 00:53:20,409
Rym: So like scan in an essay and then be able to search through the text in that essay like it's a text file, not like it's an image.

655
00:53:21,253 --> 00:53:21,494
Scott: Right.

656
00:53:21,575 --> 00:53:25,090
Scott: So the software to do OCR has gotten better over time.

657
00:53:25,331 --> 00:53:26,809
Scott: The image resolution is better.

658
00:53:27,251 --> 00:53:36,610
Scott: So that especially if you're OCRing something that was printed right out of another computer or is like an officially printed document, it's in English especially.

659
00:53:37,374 --> 00:53:39,070
Scott: And you're using modern software.

660
00:53:39,793 --> 00:53:41,950
Scott: The results are going to be very, very good.

661
00:53:42,210 --> 00:53:43,470
Rym: This used to not be the case.

662
00:53:43,751 --> 00:53:46,329
Rym: I remember paying a lot of money as a kid.

663
00:53:47,072 --> 00:53:48,717
Rym: Well, our family to get.

664
00:53:48,778 --> 00:53:52,490
Rym: so I forget what it was called, but there were some OCR softwares you could buy.

665
00:53:52,831 --> 00:53:53,032
Scott: Oh, yeah.

666
00:53:53,112 --> 00:53:57,110
Scott: In the 90s, you could get on CD-ROM, you could buy an OCR thing and it's like they work kinda.

667
00:53:57,410 --> 00:53:58,910
Rym: They work kinda is the way I'd say.

668
00:53:58,955 --> 00:53:59,068
Rym: Okay.

669
00:53:59,270 --> 00:54:00,709
Rym: I pirated one that worked better.

670
00:54:00,970 --> 00:54:06,850
Scott: It worked well enough that it was better to do that and then correct the document than to just type it all in by hand.

671
00:54:07,274 --> 00:54:07,464
Rym: Yeah.

672
00:54:07,791 --> 00:54:09,430
Scott: But it was still a pain in the ass.

673
00:54:09,610 --> 00:54:12,330
Scott: Nowadays, you might barely have to type anything in my hand at all.

674
00:54:12,572 --> 00:54:14,970
Rym: Adobe Acrobat in particular just does it.

675
00:54:15,130 --> 00:54:25,830
Rym: If I scan a document and it sees it's a document, it automatically does all the OCR it can and it is just 100% accurate unless my document is really fucked up.

676
00:54:26,610 --> 00:54:27,749
Scott: Or the scan is fucked up.

677
00:54:29,410 --> 00:54:35,070
Scott: But the place the OCR matters the most is when you want to scan a printed book into an e-book.

678
00:54:36,111 --> 00:54:47,470
Scott: And so that's where you have libraries and places have these special book scanners that basically hold the book open, take photos of both pages, turn the page, take photos of both pages.

679
00:54:47,550 --> 00:54:51,790
Rym: And that's where you get into non-destructive scanning versus destructive scanning.

680
00:54:52,070 --> 00:54:57,670
Rym: Like tearing a book apart to scan it will be better than carefully scanning it in a way that doesn't destroy it.

681
00:54:58,270 --> 00:55:00,530
Scott: But if it's a rare special book, you can't do that.

682
00:55:00,952 --> 00:55:01,188
Rym: Exactly.

683
00:55:01,330 --> 00:55:03,650
Scott: Whereas if it's a normal old book, it's like go right ahead.

684
00:55:03,990 --> 00:55:04,058
Rym: Yup.

685
00:55:04,311 --> 00:55:08,870
Scott: But if it's a newer book, you don't even need to do that because it started life as an e-book.

686
00:55:09,410 --> 00:55:19,590
Scott: It's only this narrow few decades of books that were printed but they're not rare and valuable so we can tear apart one copy of each to get them scanned.

687
00:55:21,231 --> 00:55:26,090
Rym: But also people's pipelines are different in terms of what they do with documents.

688
00:55:27,313 --> 00:55:29,230
Rym: Most people don't even have a desktop computer anymore.

689
00:55:29,330 --> 00:55:30,930
Rym: A lot of people don't even have laptops anymore.

690
00:55:31,070 --> 00:55:36,230
Rym: So increasingly I think the way people will scan things, like one, they won't have photos to scan anymore.

691
00:55:36,810 --> 00:55:46,490
Rym: Physical photos to scan are just because we're old enough to have physical photos lying around or a relative dies and you get their pile of physical photos.

692
00:55:46,570 --> 00:55:49,689
Rym: You realize no one ever scanned them in and you scan them all in in one go.

693
00:55:50,570 --> 00:55:56,930
Scott: So I think this is what we're seeing is like, you know, even though there's still plenty of stuff in the world that needs scanning, right?

694
00:55:57,851 --> 00:55:59,959
Scott: We're seeing people who are younger than us.

695
00:56:00,059 --> 00:56:03,130
Scott: Their whole lives did not include anything that needs scanning.

696
00:56:03,490 --> 00:56:04,694
Rym: Yeah, mostly the teenagers today.

697
00:56:04,855 --> 00:56:08,870
Rym: There's nothing, there's no essay they wrote by hand that they will ever need.

698
00:56:08,890 --> 00:56:11,820
Scott: They've never received a paper bill in the mail.

699
00:56:11,860 --> 00:56:13,666
Scott: They've never filed taxes on paper.

700
00:56:13,726 --> 00:56:14,810
Scott: They've never done any, right?

701
00:56:14,850 --> 00:56:17,016
Scott: It's like there's nothing in their lives to scan.

702
00:56:17,056 --> 00:56:21,990
Scott: So it's really an older generation of people that have paper things to scan in their lives.

703
00:56:22,511 --> 00:56:29,410
Scott: And if they either A) scan everything, then they don't need a scanner anymore because their lives are now digital or B) they die.

704
00:56:30,290 --> 00:56:32,356
Scott: And now it's like, well, that's it.

705
00:56:33,058 --> 00:56:37,030
Scott: So the only people who really need scanners now, right?

706
00:56:37,150 --> 00:56:44,330
Scott: In this world where people are living fully digital lives are people who are still living in parts of the world where it's not fully digital and they're going to transition.

707
00:56:44,530 --> 00:56:45,568
Scott: They haven't made this transition yet.

708
00:56:45,690 --> 00:56:48,290
Rym: Or people with professional interests.

709
00:56:48,430 --> 00:56:55,450
Scott: Right, archivists, you know, artists, photographers, someone with some reason, right, to scan.

710
00:56:55,931 --> 00:57:03,530
Scott: And so, you know, we probably could make, if they wanted to, like really fucking amazing scanners if someone really tried.

711
00:57:03,971 --> 00:57:13,230
Scott: But just the use case, the demand is already dropping off and is only going to drop off further as, you know, it's like scanning solved this temporary problem.

712
00:57:13,932 --> 00:57:19,746
Scott: And it's there for those who need it and fewer and fewer and fewer people need it as time goes on.

713
00:57:19,766 --> 00:57:20,909
Scott: And that's it.

714
00:57:21,430 --> 00:57:22,255
Rym: Like what do I scan now?

715
00:57:22,315 --> 00:57:25,190
Rym: Like after I did all that big bulk scanning of all my old documents.

716
00:57:25,730 --> 00:57:27,839
Rym: Like I got some work done in my car recently.

717
00:57:27,960 --> 00:57:30,210
Rym: The guy had a paper bill.

718
00:57:30,991 --> 00:57:32,069
Scott: He didn't email you the thing?

719
00:57:32,510 --> 00:57:33,173
Rym: Nah.

720
00:57:33,193 --> 00:57:37,630
Rym: He emailed me videos of all the work he did, but the actual bill and everything was a printout.

721
00:57:38,150 --> 00:57:41,190
Rym: So I scanned it and then I shredded that document.

